  "topic_name": "Human Body: Circulatory System",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "The circulatory system transports blood, nutrients, gases, and waste products throughout the body. Blood consists of plasma (55%) and cellular components (45%): red blood cells (carry oxygen), white blood cells (immunity), and platelets (clotting). The heart is a four-chambered muscular organ with two atria and two ventricles, separated by valves. The cardiac cycle involves systole (contraction) and diastole (relaxation). Blood flows through arteries (from heart), capillaries (exchange), and veins (to heart). Pulmonary circulation carries blood between heart and lungs; systemic circulation carries blood between heart and body. Blood clotting involves platelets, prothrombin, thrombin, and fibrin. Blood groups (ABO and Rh) determine transfusion compatibility.",
    "rules": [
      "Blood consists of plasma, RBCs, WBCs, and platelets",
      "RBCs carry oxygen bound to hemoglobin; have no nucleus; live about 120 days",
      "WBCs are part of the immune system; types include neutrophils, lymphocytes, monocytes",
      "Platelets are cell fragments involved in blood clotting",
      "Heart has four chambers: two atria (receive blood) and two ventricles (pump blood)",
      "Tricuspid valve is between right atrium and ventricle; bicuspid between left atrium and ventricle",
      "SA node is the pacemaker that initiates heartbeat",
      "Arteries carry blood away from heart; veins carry blood to heart",
      "Pulmonary artery carries deoxygenated blood; pulmonary vein carries oxygenated blood",
      "Type O is universal donor; Type AB is universal recipient"
    ]
  },
